Source:  Maori Death Customs
Author:  OPPENHEiM
Vol / Page:  64
Edition:
Quote:  [Hdg] The Display of the Bones (Hahunga). ibid 70 in the northern tradition the time lapse between primary burial and Hahunga could be anything from a few months to several years.
Notes:

Date:  23/5/1828
Source:  Early Journals of Henry Williams, The
Author:  WiLLiAMS
Vol / Page:  130
Edition:  1961
Quote:  Tekoke and most of the natives of the settlement  had left to attend a Hahunga at Taeamai. ... [131 May 30] ... two messengers arrived from Waimate ...  to request our attendance at the Ha'hunga ... <i>ibid.</i> 244 The Chiefs Hiamoe and Pukututu came from the Kauakaua to request some of us to go up to attend the  Hahunga there, the feast which takes place at the removal of the bones of the dead.
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1835
Source:  New Zealand (various authors/titles)
Author:  YATE
Vol / Page:  137
Edition:
Quote:  Hahunga, a grand annual feast ... No further notice is taken of the deceased till the Hahunga, a grand annual feast; when the [138] bones of all belonging to several united tribes are taken down, and removed to their last resting-place, in or near the sacred grove.
Notes:  (Griffiths Collection)

Date:  0/0/1856
Source:  Traditions & Superstitions
Author:  SHORTLAND
Vol / Page:  147
Edition:
Quote:  A very curious ceremony, called hahunga, takes place when the skulls of the dead are exhibited to their living relations before being finally deposited in the secret family vault.
Notes:

